<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="135" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Known only from the Bamenwan mangrove forest of Hainan Prov., China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="135" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="135">
Female specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia bamenwana" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamenwana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia bamenwana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
run to genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the key of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1051/parasite/1974495595" author="Wirth, WW" journalOrPublisher="Annales de Parasitologie (Paris)" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="595 - 613" refId="B11" refString="Wirth, WW, Ratanaworabhan, NC, Blanton, FS, 1974. Synopsis of the genera of Ceratopogonidae (Diptera). Annales de Parasitologie (Paris) 49: 595 - 613" title="Synopsis of the genera of Ceratopogonidae (Diptera)." url="https://doi.org/10.1051/parasite/1974495595" volume="49" year="1974">Wirth et al. (1974)</bibRefCitation>
and conforms to the diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
provided by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1071/AJZS028" author="Debenham, ML" journalOrPublisher="Australian Journal of Zoology Supplementary Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="1 - 92" refId="B3" refString="Debenham, ML, 1974. A revision of the Australian and New Guinea predatory Ceratopogonidae (Diptera: Nematocera) of the tribes Heteromyiini and Sphaeromiini. Australian Journal of Zoology Supplementary Series 22: 1 - 92" title="A revision of the Australian and New Guinea predatory Ceratopogonidae (Diptera: Nematocera) of the tribes Heteromyiini and Sphaeromiini." url="https://doi.org/10.1071/AJZS028" volume="22" year="1974">Debenham (1974)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirth, WW" journalOrPublisher="Pacific Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="396 - 431" refId="B10" refString="Wirth, WW, Ratanaworabhan, NC, 1981. New species and records of predaceous midges (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae) from rice paddies in Thailand. Pacific Insects 23: 396 - 431" title="New species and records of predaceous midges (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae) from rice paddies in Thailand." volume="23" year="1981">Wirth and Ratanaworabhan (1981)</bibRefCitation>
. The only other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recorded from mangrove forest is 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. virago" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="virago">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">N. virago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Debenham which was recorded from many different habitats including a single female specimen collected from mangroves in Australia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1071/AJZS028" author="Debenham, ML" journalOrPublisher="Australian Journal of Zoology Supplementary Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="1 - 92" refId="B3" refString="Debenham, ML, 1974. A revision of the Australian and New Guinea predatory Ceratopogonidae (Diptera: Nematocera) of the tribes Heteromyiini and Sphaeromiini. Australian Journal of Zoology Supplementary Series 22: 1 - 92" title="A revision of the Australian and New Guinea predatory Ceratopogonidae (Diptera: Nematocera) of the tribes Heteromyiini and Sphaeromiini." url="https://doi.org/10.1071/AJZS028" volume="22" year="1974">Debenham 1974</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="135">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia bamenwana" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamenwana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia bamenwana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
runs to 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. acanthopus" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="acanthopus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">N. acanthopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(de Meijere) in the key to Southeast Asian species by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wirth, WW" journalOrPublisher="Pacific Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="396 - 431" refId="B10" refString="Wirth, WW, Ratanaworabhan, NC, 1981. New species and records of predaceous midges (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae) from rice paddies in Thailand. Pacific Insects 23: 396 - 431" title="New species and records of predaceous midges (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae) from rice paddies in Thailand." volume="23" year="1981">Wirth and Ratanaworabhan (1981)</bibRefCitation>
but in the latter species the forefemur and midfemur are entirely yellowish and the spermathecae are equal in size. India has 18 described species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mazumdar, A" journalOrPublisher="Entomologist's Monthly Magazine" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="131 - 151" refId="B7" refString="Mazumdar, A, Chaudhuri, PK, Das Gupta, SK, 2009. New insectivorous midges of the genus Nilobezzia Kieffer from India (Dipt., Ceratopogonidae: Sphaeromiini). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine 145: 131 - 151" title="New insectivorous midges of the genus Nilobezzia Kieffer from India (Dipt., Ceratopogonidae: Sphaeromiini)." volume="145" year="2009">Mazumdar et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
), some of which possess similar leg colour patterns and other characteristics to 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. bamenwana" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="bamenwana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">N. bamenwana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but with wings shorter than 2.5 mm and significantly smaller than 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. bamenwana" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="bamenwana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">N. bamenwana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and none appear to be associated with mangroves. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia bamenwana" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamenwana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia bamenwana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
runs to 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. opaca" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="opaca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">N. opaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Das Gupta in the key by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mazumdar, A" journalOrPublisher="Entomologist's Monthly Magazine" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" pagination="131 - 151" refId="B7" refString="Mazumdar, A, Chaudhuri, PK, Das Gupta, SK, 2009. New insectivorous midges of the genus Nilobezzia Kieffer from India (Dipt., Ceratopogonidae: Sphaeromiini). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine 145: 131 - 151" title="New insectivorous midges of the genus Nilobezzia Kieffer from India (Dipt., Ceratopogonidae: Sphaeromiini)." volume="145" year="2009">Mazumdar et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, but that species can be distinguished by the obvious neck of spermathecae and legs excepting the midfemora, entirely brown. It runs to 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. formosana" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="formosana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">N. formosana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Kieffer) in the key to Chinese species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Yu, YX" journalOrPublisher="Military Medical Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" refId="B12" refString="Yu, YX, Liu, JH, Liu, GP, Liu, ZJ, Hao, BS, Yan, G, Zhao, TS, 2005. Ceratopogonidae of China - Insecta, Diptera [in Chinese]. Military Medical Science Press, Beijing" title="Ceratopogonidae of China - Insecta, Diptera [in Chinese]." year="2005">Yu et al. (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, but that species is much smaller in size with a wing length of only 2.11 mm. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Nilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nilobezzia bamenwana" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamenwana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">Nilobezzia bamenwana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is allied to 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. japana" pageId="0" pageNumber="135" rank="species" species="japana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="135">N. japana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tokunaga in general colour, but the latter species is smaller (body length 3.2 mm), has more extensive dark markings on the forefemur and midfemur, and the foretibia lacks spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
